==English==

===Etymology===
{{PIE root|en|wedʰ}}
From {{inh|en|enm|wedden}}, {{m|enm|weddien}}, from {{inh|en|ang|weddian||to pledge; wed}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*wadjōną||to pledge}}, from {{m|gem-pro|*wadją}}, ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*wedʰ-||to pledge}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|wed}}, {{m|sco|wod}}, {{m|sco|wad||to wed}}, {{cog|stq|wädje||to bet, wager}}, {{cog|fy|wedzje||to bet, wager}}, Low German and Dutch {{m|nl|wedden||to bet}}, German {{m|de|wetten||to bet}}, Danish {{m|da|vædde||to bet}}, Swedish {{m|sv|vädja||to appeal}}, Icelandic {{m|is|veðja||to bet}}. Related also to {{l|en|gage}}, {{l|en|engage}}, and {{l|en|wage}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|wĕdʹ}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈwɛd/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-wed.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɛd}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|weds|wedding|wedded|past2=wed}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To perform the [[marriage]] ceremony for; to join in [[matrimony]].
#: ''The priest '''wed''' the couple.''
#* {{rfdatek|en|John Milton}}
#*: And Adam, '''wedded''' to another Eve, / Shall live with her.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To take as one's [[spouse]].
#: ''She '''wed''' her first love.''
#* '''2017''' September 27, David Browne, "[http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/hugh-hefner-playboy-founder-dead-at-91-w443922 Hugh Hefner, 'Playboy' Founder, Dead at 91]," ''Rolling Stone''
#*:  In 1989, he '''wed''' Playmate Kimberley Conrad, a marriage that ended in 2010. In 2013, he married his younger girlfriend, Crystal Harris, with whom he was still '''wed''' at the time of his death.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To take a spouse.
# {{lb|en|figuratively|transitive}} To [[join]] or [[commit]] to, more or less permanently, as if in marriage.
#: ''I'm not '''wedded''' to this proposal; suggest an alternative.''
#*{{RQ:Shakespeare Romeo and Juliet|act=III|scene=iii|passage=Affliction is enamoured of thy parts, and thou art '''wedded''' to calamity.}}
#* {{rfdatek|en|Tillotson}}
#*: Men are '''wedded''' to their lusts.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2008|author=Bradley Simpson|title=Economists with Guns| page=72| passage={{...}} the PPS paper proposed a political doctrine that '''wedded''' modernization theory to U.S. support for national security states {{...}}}}
# {{lb|en|figurative|intransitive}} To take to oneself and support; to [[espouse]].
#* {{rfdatek|en|Clarendon}}
#*: They positively and concernedly '''wedded''' his cause.
# {{lb|en|Northern England|Scotland}} To [[wager]], [[stake]], [[bet]], [[place]] a [[bet]], [[make]] a [[wager]].
#: {{ux|en|I'd '''wed''' my head on that.}}

